[2] Oregon: horse
Date: 13 Sep 2021
Source: The Chronicle Online [edited]
https://www.thechronicleonline.com/news/horse-diseases-highly-contagious-ehv-1-found-in-oregon/article_b4c69b9c-1283-11ec-9dac-e32aa2348fe9.html


The ODA [Oregon Department of Agriculture] received 6 confirmed reports of West Nile virus (WNV) diagnosed in Oregon horses in the past 2 weeks.

One additional suspected case is under investigation. The affected horses live in multiple counties throughout the state: Umatilla, Malheur, and Klamath. None of the infected horses were recently vaccinated against WNV, and most of the horses have never been vaccinated for WNV.

Numerous additional WNV cases have also been reported recently in Washington, Idaho, and California near the Oregon border. Therefore, ODA advises annual vaccination as an effective tool for preventing WNV infection in horses.

West Nile virus is a reportable disease in Oregon. Veterinarians must report suspected cases to the Oregon State Veterinarian.

[The ODA also confirmed new cases of EHV-1 in Oregon. Please see the equine herpesvirus report on ProMED for information on the horse with EHV, archive 20210923.8695753). - Mod.TG]

